<h1><a href="/2013/10/01/passions-photography-dancing-coding-anna-marie-chicago/">When Passions For Photography, Dancing, And Coding Come Together</a></h1>
<p>Posted at 01 Oct 2013 by Staff</p>
</div>
<div class="share-btns">
<div>
<a href="https://twitter.com/share" class="twitter-share-button" data-via="devbootcamp">Tweet</a>
</div>
<div>
<div id="fb-root"></div>
<div class="fb-like" data-send="false" data-layout="button_count" data-width="1" data-show-faces="false" data-action="like"></div>
</div>
<div>
<script class="linkedin-share" type="IN/Share" data-counter="right" data-showzero="true"></script>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="article-post">
<h2><em>"What I learned at DBC Chicago was how to learn, how to solve a problem. Now, it's up to me to keep doing it over and over so I can speak the language."</em></h2>
<p><strong>-- Anna-Marie Panlilio</strong></p>
<p><img src="http://devbootcamp.github.com/imgs/blog/alumni/annamarie-chicago.jpg" alt="Dev Bootcamp"/></p>
<p>Today we hear from <a href="http://panlil.io">Anna Marie Panlilio</a>, dancer, photographer, and recent graduate of Dev Bootcamp Chicago. Dev Bootcamp students share a common love for coding, but how each individual student came to that love is always a unique story. In our Alumni in Action series we invite graduates of Dev Bootcamp to share some of their personal story.</p>
<p>Anna Marie talked with us about following her passions for dancing and photography, the differences between working with early html more than a decade ago and learning Ruby on Rails now, and the big realization that helped her succeed at Dev Bootcamp.</p>
<p><img src="http://devbootcamp.github.com/imgs/blog/alumni/anna-marie-pic.png" alt="Dev Bootcamp"/></p>
<h2>Tell us a little bit about your background.</h2>
<p><em>I like to immerse myself in things I'm interested in and see them through to places I never expected.</em> I have a rich history, much of it in dance, photography, and web work.</p>
<p>For example, I grew up dancing as a young girl. I auditioned for a lot of things and kept getting rejected. They’d say, “You’re not good enough” or “You don’t have enough energy” and things like that. But I loved it, so I kept doing it, going to classes and learning.</p>
<p>After graduating from Northwestern, I was planning to come back to California and look for a job doing web stuff. But one of my dance professors was starting a new dance company so I auditioned and got in. I stayed in Chicago, and it was amazing. I danced with them for four years, and I learned so much. At the same time I was working in the John Hancock Building doing early html work with a team there. It was a great life.</p>
<h2>How did you get into photography?</h2>
<p>I got interested while I was dancing, especially in the photography of dance. At one point I studied in Italy, but the program there wasn't a great fit. They wanted to help me come up with a vision, but I already had that -- I could see the pictures I wanted to take in my mind.</p>
<p>They didn't have the technical chops to teach me what I wanted to learn so I came back and worked in web and graphic design roles. Meanwhile I took photography courses at community colleges, picking up the technical skills that I wasn’t able to get in Italy. I kept shooting and doing side projects.</p>
<p>After a few years I was working as the presentation person for a VP in Southern California and one day I just said okay, I’m going to do it. I moved up to San Francisco with the goal that in ten years I would be a professional dance photographer. That was in 2005.</p>
<p>Going to a 2-day workshop in New York with my favorite dance photographer in 2007 is what really got the ball rolling. She brought in professional dancers, and I got behind the camera and started directing them. At that point I realized “I can do this.” This isn't a pipe dream.</p>
<p>I came back to California and started calling all my dancer friends and saying, “Hey, I’m going to do some photos. Do you want to play around in the studio with me?” I just kept practicing and shooting a lot, sharing my photos online and getting enough people interested to the point where I would just have people say, “Hey, I need pictures done."</p>
<p>And now, in the fall of 2013, I just had 16 new photographs go up in an art exhibit, so I’m happy to say I made my goal happen in less than the ten years. Here I am doing it. Maybe not full-time, but I’m doing it.</p>
<h2>What was your catalyst for applying to Dev Bootcamp?</h2>
<p>Sitting in corporate offices and saying to myself, <em>“I can’t live my life like this anymore. I know what it’s like on the other side, to have rich experiences, and I want that in a working environment. How can I get that?”</em></p>
<p>I've had a variety of jobs in large corporations doing work that wasn't fulfilling. I would walk into these offices and shut off a part of myself. I found myself going through a day without laughing, or sometimes without even smiling. Walking down the hallway and having coworkers give a half smile, if they even looked up at all.</p>
<p>I started thinking, “When was I really happy at a job?” It was on that web team, back in Chicago after I first graduated. We had a lot of fun. We worked hard. We did things on deadline. We <em>made</em> things. But I knew that my skills weren’t there anymore because technology moves so fast.</p>
<p>I heard about Dev Bootcamp and similar boot camps, and I had this hunch that it would be the right place for me.</p>
<p><em>I chose Dev Bootcamp because of the engineering empathy and the emphasis on soft skills, or the inclusion of soft skills, which I didn’t see was happening anywhere else.</em></p>
<h2>What was your experience like?</h2>
<p>During the month leading up to DBC starting I was conceptualizing and shooting the series for my art show in San Francisco. It was a tough transition because it was right before I left for Chicago. I knew once I got to Dev Bootcamp I wouldn't have any time for it.</p>
<p>I spent a lot of time clearing my plate so that I could be fully present at Dev Bootcamp. That meant shooting a ton of photography and not prepping enough for Dev Bootcamp. Because of that, my first week felt like I was drowning. I felt really behind. I kept thinking, "I don’t know if I can hack it… I don’t know if I can stay." They give you that week to decide whether or not you’re going to stay or not.</p>
<p>But then that Friday (Day 5) at lunchtime, two of the people in the cohort ahead of me (nicknamed the squirrels), made an announcement that the squirrels wanted to pair with us newbies over the weekend. They put up a whiteboard with their names, time-slots, and they said, “Sign up if you want to pair.”</p>
<p><em>All of a sudden this weight came off of my shoulders. “What? I can get help? I can go at a different pace? That’s when I decided that I was going to stay. If this is what it’s like, then yes, I’m still going to be going crazy, but at least I’m not all on my own.</em></p>
<p>For all nine weeks, every weekend I paired with a "squirrel" in some way or another. Meeting the first cohort in Chicago was amazing. They were so tight as a group, just cohesive and having fun. You could see they were just really loving it there and really setting the culture in a great way.</p>
<p>It didn't take long for me to realize that the goldmine of Dev Bootcamp, or at least one of them, is the people.</p>
<p>When incoming cohorts come in, we’re asked to offer advice. Mine was that people are the magic sauce. You can learn something from anyone here. Just take advantage of that.</p>
<h2>You talk about Engineering Empathy as one of the reasons that you picked that boot camp, in the first place. How did that play out in your experience?</h2>
<p>One of the conversations I had when I paired with a Squirrel that first weekend was about how his cohort got so close. My cohort, that'd been there for five days, was still very much strangers to each other. He attributed it to improv and things like that, but I noticed that it happened with us after the third engineering empathy session. I observed the group dynamic of the cohorts that followed and noticed a similar pattern.</p>
<p>I had met the Squirrels after they had gone through all three of those empathy sessions.</p>
<p><em>Once you start having those conversations when you're below the waterline and you're telling things to people that you probably haven't told to anyone in your life, you really have no choice but to bond.</em> I mean, you have the choice, but if you can empathize with them, you're going to break down those walls, and that's what happened.</p>
<h2>You had done web design before with static web pages, and you characterized your skills as no longer relevant or up to date. I don't want to put words in your mouth. Was it a help or a hindrance to have a background in web design?</h2>
<p>Definitely a big help. Especially when it got to phase two and we started doing front end challenges. The CSS didn't faze me. I was able to help our group projects come together at least by making them look nice on the front. Then, also having an understanding of what the pieces are.</p>
<p>Even though I didn't know the backend before, I knew how to implement websites pretty well. I'd taken other people's code and made it work before.</p>
<h2>Is there an overlap between dance, photography, and coding?</h2>
<p>Sure. Where I am right now as this world class beginner is a place I've been with both dance and photography. The way that I got better at both of those was by doing it as much as possible and not giving up. Focusing, sticking with it, and practicing until it becomes engrained.</p>
<p>I freeze people in motion in photography where I have them suspended in mid-air. You have to have certain technical things in order to take a shot like that. I shoot everything on manual. I can pick up the camera and know exactly how to adjust so that I get the shot that I want the first time, as long as they jump well the first time, that is. It's now second nature because of all the times that I have done it.</p>
<p><em>I think it's the same as programming. What I learned at DBC Chicago was how to learn, how to solve a problem. Now, it's up to me to keep doing it over and over so I can speak the language.</em></p>
<p>It reminds me of when I was in Italy and learning Italian. I took a train to Rome from Florence by myself one weekend. I got off at the train stop and asked one of the workers, “Where is bus number 4?” in Italian. He responded back to me in Italian. I was so excited because he knew what I was saying even though I had no idea what his answer was. I just smiled this huge smile. I was like, "Yeah. Wow. Wait, I have no idea what he just said."</p>
<p>One morning after four months in Italy when I was back in America, I woke up from a dream that was all in Italian. I was thrilled. I'm hoping that'll happen with code too.</p>
<h2>Is there anything else you think people thinking about Dev Bootcamp should know?</h2>
<p>It’s a very social learning environment, and if that’s something that’s not for you, you might have a hard time. I don’t think it matters if you're an introvert or an extrovert. I think introverts can succeed really well at boot camp. I’m not an extrovert. I think before I speak but I’m a social learner, and I thrive in team environments.</p>
<p><em>You pair program everyday at DBC. One of the benefits is you can get through a lot more together then you can on your own so definitely consider Dev Bootcamp if that’s something that you think you would enjoy.</em></p>
</div>
</div>
