<h1><a href="/2013/09/19/alexis-mural-dev-bootcamp-chicago-mural/">THINK HERE! You've Never Seen A Mural Like What Alexis Finch Made For DBC Chicago</a></h1>
<p>Posted at 19 Sep 2013 by Staff</p>
</div>
<div class="share-btns">
<div>
<a href="https://twitter.com/share" class="twitter-share-button" data-via="devbootcamp">Tweet</a>
</div>
<div>
<div id="fb-root"></div>
<div class="fb-like" data-send="false" data-layout="button_count" data-width="1" data-show-faces="false" data-action="like"></div>
</div>
<div>
<script class="linkedin-share" type="IN/Share" data-counter="right" data-showzero="true"></script>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="article-post">
<h2><em>"I wanted to create something fun, something to lighten a hard day, a space that gave everyone the permission to play, to joke around."</em> -- Alexis Finch</h2>
<p><img src="http://devbootcamp.github.com/imgs/blog/alexis/dbc-chi-mural.jpg" alt="Dev Bootcamp"/></p>
<p>If you visit Dev Bootcamp Chicago, you'll see an eight foot high mural amidst the red brick where the door for a freight elevator once was. At this point it's embedded in DBC Chicago school culture. It's a space where graduating students leave advice, where current students share inspiring quotes, or where people can take a break and just play. But when Dave Hoover, director of DBC Chicago, was putting together the Chicago vision, that old freight elevator was just a big square of bland drywall.</p>
<p><em>"For some reason the blank square made me think of Instagram, and I thought it would be a cool blackboard space. The idea was to inspire and invite people to create and think in public.</em></p>
<p><em>I've known Alexis for years and she does some amazing things with sketch notes. She did what we commissioned her to do, and then she just kept going. She did things I never expected and it turned out amazing. And she did it the day before she moved to New York, so it's cool that this was kind of her final act in Chicago. She signed her name and then the next day she was off!"</em></p>
<p>Watch an awesome timelapse creation of the mural set to music here: <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d9Vg13RENK0">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d9Vg13RENK0</a></p>
<p>I got the chance to talk with Alexis Finch herself and learn more about how and why she uses sketch notes, her process in making the DBC mural, and what she's working on next.</p>
<p><img src="http://devbootcamp.github.com/imgs/blog/alexis/alexis.jpg" alt="Dev Bootcamp"/></p>
<h2>What were you trying to create with the DBC Chicago mural?</h2>
<p>Signing on to DBC is a huge commitment. These students are dedicating themselves to nine weeks of work, day in day out focused on reaching a level of aptitude that normally takes years to achieve. What's more, these aren't just facts and figures they're learning. They're teaching their minds to solve problems in completely different ways, in a new language... while on a deadline.</p>
<p><em>I wanted to create something fun, something to lighten a hard day, a space that gave everyone the permission to play, to joke around.</em></p>
<p>The whole mural is a series of inside jokes about Ruby on Rails. I've been sketchnoting technology talks for the past three years and coming from the outside, there are a lot of terms that I've always found funny. I like playing with language, so for this I took the visual metaphors I've used in other sketchnotes and stretched them a bit more. I also wanted to be sure there were a few "easy" spaces for people to contribute. That's what the faces are for, as well as the "how to draw a dinosaur" instructions.</p>
<p><em>I teach sketchnote classes, and the biggest challenge is always getting folks past the idea that only artists can draw. Anyone can draw! They just need somewhere to start.</em></p>
<p>So, that's what I was trying to create: an opening.</p>
<h2>What was your experience creating the mural there like?</h2>
<p>Wow. It was, to say the least, intense.</p>
<p><em>I had this blank wall and the challenge of creating something that DBC would be proud to have not just for a few weeks, but for class after class.</em></p>
<p>It needed to be engaging, but also not distracting. I had a few ideas at the beginning, bits and phrases that I knew I wanted to include, but staring at a blank wall is always intimidating. I made a few rough sketches, but on the timeline I had, there wasn't time to go through a bunch of iterations. The DBC space wasn't even finished yet, and I was mainly working through the night, so from the start, it was a very surreal environment to be in. Big glass windows, lights from the city, an empty office.</p>
<p>The soundtrack to the time-lapse is two songs by <a href="https://soundcloud.com/alt-j">Alt-J</a>. I'd just discovered them from an NPR piece and liked the way the whole album kind of pulls you along. I had that album playing on repeat, through my crappy laptop speakers, the whole time I was painting.</p>
<p><img src="http://devbootcamp.github.com/imgs/blog/alexis/alexis-muraling.png" alt="Dev Bootcamp"/></p>
<p><em>Sketchnoting for me is meditational process, hearing what the speaker is saying, but letting it all kind of flow past, grabbing the important parts and interpreting them on the fly.</em></p>
<p>It's a very different feeling, but once I had the general layout on the wall, that same almost trance state took over. I'd be painting and then realize the sun had come up.</p>
<p><em>There's always that feeling, when you're getting close to completing a piece, where it's more like you're excavating a building. I've heard people talk about programming this way as well, when you already know the structure of what you need to code and the rest kind of falls into place.</em></p>
<p>It was hard to walk away from the piece at the end. I didn't want that feeling to be over, but at some point, you just have to sign your name and walk away. Build and ship, right?</p>
<h2>How did you get started with sketch notes in the first place?</h2>
<p><em>I'm incredibly lucky for having gone to a very strange school for seventh through twelfth grade. While in other schools teachers would punish kids for doodling, we were encouraged to.</em></p>
<p>Everyone took art classes, so it was natural that while we were learning to draw that would creep into our notes in other classes. My art teacher, Rob Logan, was very adamant about tearing down the idea of 'the artist.' He got all of us sketching no matter if we loved it from the start or not. My notes back then in school were always filled with boxes and arrows and faces, and I'd remember things we'd talked about in class from the image I'd drawn next to the date I needed to remember.</p>
<p>I found out years later that a fellow classmate, Sita Magnuson, had started working at a company that did Graphic Facilitation. She'd be hired by a company to visually document a business meeting or summit, capturing the ideas, leading discussion in a productive direction by providing visual anchors for what was being said. I thought that was pretty amazing, so I started doing the same kind of thing in my sketchbook. This was around the same time that <a href="http://www.imagethink.net/technology/sketchnotes-at-sxsw-v2v/">Image Think got brought to SXSW</a> to visualize the talks there.</p>
<p>I guess what surprised me was how much people liked the notes I was taking, so I started posting them up online and asking around to see if anyone would like me to come in and cover their talks. Since I was involved in the tech scene in Chicago, most of those were tech talks, starting with Dave inviting me to Obtiva's <a href="https://twitter.com/geekfest">Geekfests</a>.</p>
<h2>Why do you think it's beneficial for people to use sketch notes ?</h2>
<p>We're all visual thinkers at heart. Two-thirds of our brain is dedicated to processing visual information. We're pretty good at remembering what we see, be it a particular car, or a person's face. Reading is already visual, interpreting symbols into meaningful ideas. What's interesting is when you tie images, particularly metaphor based ones, in with words to explain a new idea. By creating references to thing you already know, recall of the new idea is improved.</p>
<p><em>There's been a lot of study on how just moving a pencil across a page can improve recall of information someone is listening to. I think a lot of that is just giving idle hands something to do. It's like fidgeting. You're getting rid of excess energy which would otherwise wind up being a distraction.</em></p>
<p>Taking that idle movement and focusing it into a documentation of what you're hearing, that creates a secondary path of recall of the information your'e taking in. You might remember what you heard, but you also remember what you thought about what you were hearing. When the sketchnotes I do are paired with a talk, even though the person looking at them didn't create them, they get a kind of road map of what they've just learned.</p>
<p>Looking at a sketchnote while listening to a talk also works to focus the mind on what information is going to be important. It's like having a someone standing alongside the speaker saying <em>"Ok, now this part is going to be important."</em></p>
<p>By doing all this with metaphor, there's the bonus of making what might be a really confusing topic a bit more approachable. I break down the big ideas into smaller things that are relatable, and hence rememberable.</p>
<h2>What's your favorite thing you've learned about how sketch notes facilitate note-taking?</h2>
<p>Really it's that they can help anyone. You don't have to be a 'professional' to do them, or a 'real artist.' You don't even need to include all the faces and dinosaurs. Just making your notes visually engaging, putting effort into selecting the words you write down, that's enough to boost recall.</p>
<p><em>It's funny to think that if all was right in the world, my work wouldn't be needed at all. Everyone would be doing sketchnotes all the time, so why would they need to bring me in?</em></p>
<h2>What are you working on now?</h2>
<p>I've been doing a bunch of work for <a href="http://500.co/">500startups</a>. I created sketchnotes of all twenty-nine companies in their last batch, pulling from their demo day pitches as well as information on their websites. That was a big challenge, again creating images not just from what someone was saying, but really building out the story for each company through visuals. Pitches have to spend so much time on funding and user adoption, but I needed to show what each company really did.</p>
<p>It was a big job, but I'm excited to get to do more work like that. It ties back to the UX research and strategy consulting I do, so there's something very satisfying about that. Using more parts of my brain at once, drawing from multiple skill sets.</p>
<h2>Where would you send someone interested in learning more about sketch notes?</h2>
<p>I do teach classes and workshops on visual thinking, not just to learn to do sketchotes, but how to interpret and create infographics and an intro to prototyping. I encourage everyone to just get a sketchbook and a pencil and try it out.</p>
<p><em>There's no 'wrong' way to do a sketchnote, and the more you do, the easier it gets. I actually have a hard time not sketchnoting while listening to a talk. Sometimes I even wind up grabbing some paper when a friend is talking, just because the visuals of what they're saying are so vivid.</em></p>
<p>For a crash course though, and one that you can do any time, <a href="http://rohdesign.com/">Mike Rohde</a> – who actually coined the term "sketchnote" – wrote an awesome book called <a href="http://www.peachpit.com/store/sketchnote-handbook-the-illustrated-guide-to-visual-9780321885111">"The Sketchnote Handbook."</a></p>
<p>It has exercises, tips and tricks, video tutorials, as well as a peak into his process. I was really excited that he asked me to be one of the folks to contribute a sketchnote about my own techniques and how I got into doing this crazy visual thinking thing. The book is an incredible resource and also a lot of fun to work through.</p>
<p>Of course, anyone is also always welcome to pick my brain at <a href="https://twitter.com/agentFin">@agentfin</a> on Twitter!</p>
</div>
</div>
